of this ode Scaliger pronounces that it is “ pure nectar.'’ Its beauty all admit. That it expresses any but a poetical jealousy on the part of Horace 1 do not believe. That Pyrrha was a freedwoman of exquisite beauty but loose character, and one of Horace's early loves, is all imagination, and we have no clue to the origin of 'the poem, which expresses a lover's jealousy under the pretence of being glad of escape from the toils of an inconstant mistress· Milton's translation of the ode is well known.
